            <did>
               <unittitle>Artwork</unittitle>
               <unitid>Series II</unitid>
               <physdescstructured coverage="whole" physdescstructuredtype="spaceoccupied">
                  <quantity>0.58</quantity>
                  <unittype>Linear Feet</unittype>
               </physdescstructured>
               <physdesc localtype="container_summary">(3 boxes)</physdesc>
               <unitdatestructured altrender="1924-1934" label="creation" unitdatetype="inclusive">
                  <daterange>
                     <fromdate standarddate="1924">1924</fromdate>
                     <todate standarddate="1934">1934</todate>
                  </daterange>
               </unitdatestructured>
            </did>
            <scopecontent id="aspace_8e5b842643c6f8b8883f48fc9a964e57">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>The series contains a set of ink and watercolor drawings made as illustrations for the children's book <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>Eliza and the Elves</part>
                  </title> by Rachel Field (New York: Macmillan Company, 1926), and a scrapbook kept by MacKinstry. Titled by her "Intimate Journal of Drawings 1924-1934," it contains several hundred drawings, prints, sketches, and printed ephemera affixed to the 156 pages. Media includes ink, pencil, watercolor, colored pencil, colored woodcut, and crayon on paper and card, and includes her experiments in techniques new to her (in particular, reed pen) as well as drawings made for but not used in specific books. MacKinstry also pasted-in printed dust jackets and proofs of illustrations from several projects for which illustrations or decorations were commissioned by New York publishers: <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>Semi-attached</part>
                  </title>, by Anne Parrish (George H. Doran, 1924), <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>Trees</part>
                  </title>, by Joyce Kilmer (George H. Doran, 1925), <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>The Three Owls</part>
                  </title>, by Anne Carroll Moore (Macmillan, 1925), <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>Tales of Laughter</part>
                  </title>, edited by Kate Douglas Wiggin and Nora Archibald Smith (Doubleday, Page, 1926), and <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>Snake Gold</part>
                  </title> by Hervey White (Macmillan, 1926), as well as for her own book of poetry, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>Puck in Pasture</part>
                  </title> (Doubleday, Page, 1925) . Printed ephemera includes letterhead MacKinstry designed for The Coffee Shop in New York City, a clipping from the <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>Academy Notes</part>
                  </title> (Buffalo) about an exhibition of her work, and a clipped cover from <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                     <part>The Book Dial</part>
                  </title>, vol. 3, no. 6 (1926), which features her design.</p>
            </scopecontent>
